 "nbformat": 4,
 "nbformat_minor": 2,
 "cells": [
  {
   "source": [
    "# Flux Spectrum in 2D-HFTER Full Core"
   ],
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "source": [
    "OpenMC has no functionality to tally scores in a tagged space. However, ROBIN3's OpenMC Compatibility Module can generate tallies for all cells converted from tagged region in ROBIN3 model. With post-processing functionality provided by OpenMC Compatibility Module, scores in cells of the same tag are automatically summed."
   ],
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import openmc\n",
    "import robin3\n",
    "from robin3 import openmc_compatible"
   ]
  },
  {
   "source": [
    "## Create OpenMC Model"
   ],
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "source": [
    "Firstly, load pre-defined model in [\"Modeling HFTER Full Core\" example](hfter.ipynb). Suppose that we've already export the ROBIN3 into a json file and have result file in current working directory. \n",
    " "
   ],
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "output_type": "stream",
     "name": "stdout",
     "text": [
      "HFTER.h5  hfter.json\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "!ls"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Read model from input file\n",
    "robin3_model = robin3.utils.load_data_from_file('hfter.json')[1]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "source": [
    "Add openmc_compatible parameters to model dictionary. In this example, we choose to tally flux in tagged regions."
   ],
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Add openmc_compatible parameters to model dictionary\n",
    "parameters = {'volume':'robin3', 'nuclide_density':'robin3'}\n",
    "tallies = ['flux']\n",
    "parameters['tallies'] = tallies\n",
    "robin3_model['openmc_compatible'] = parameters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "source": [
    "We've set OpenMC to calculate volumes (used to calculate tagged spaces' total volume and fissionable mass of the whole model to deduce absolute flux). The results of volume calculation will be printed during conversion. \n",
    "Caveat: do not use ROBIN3 to calculate volume if it exists several tagged regions with the same name. "
   ],
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {}
  },

  {
   "source": [
    "Now we have an OpenMC model. It is strongly recommended to use OpenMC Plot Explorer for plotting geometry, which is much faster than OpenMC Python API’s built-in plot function. The following figure shows the geometry plotted in OpenMC Plot Explorer GUI, which is identical to ROBIN3 model(except color XD)."
   ],

   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},

   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [16, 8]"
   ]
